7","about 1316":"circa 1316","1345":"1345","1453":"1453","1299":"1299","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","about 1313":"circa 1313","16 January 1369":"16 januari 1369","7 August 1363":"7 augustus 1363","about 1352":"circa 1352","1329":"1329","about 1351":"circa 1351","1328":"1328","Combe Raleigh, Devonshire, England":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Combe Raleigh, Devon, England":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1316–":"about 1316–Deceased","1314–1357":"1314–1357","1316–Male":"1316–Deceased","1329–Female":"1329–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","1352–1383":"1352–1383","1281–1345":"1281–1345","1299–Female":"1299–Deceased","20 January 1362":"20 January 1362","1352":"1352","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1281":"1281","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1314":"1314","1357":"1357","about 1316":"about 1316","1345":"1345","1453":"1453","1299":"1299","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","about 1313":"about 1313","16 January 1369":"16 January 1369","7 August 1363":"7 August 1363","about 1352":"about 1352","1329":"1329","about 1351":"about 1351","1328":"1328","Combe Raleigh, Devonshire, England":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Combe Raleigh, Devon, England":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Aubyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Andre, Normand, Armand, Cecile, Emile, Henri, Monique, Adelard, Aime, Alcid, Aldege.","French: from the personal name <i>Aubin</i> (from Latin <i>Albinus</i>, a derivative of <i>albus</i> ‘white’). This was the name of several minor early Christian saints, including a famous bishop of Angers (died <i>c.</i> 554). At an early date, this name became confused with the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Albuin</i> (see   Albin  ). Compare   Obey   and   Obin  .","English: variant of   Albin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Albin","meanings":["English, French, and German: from the personal name <i>Albin</i> (from Latin <i>Albinus</i>, a derivative of <i>albus</i> ‘white’). In England this is generally a variant of   Alban  . The usual spelling of the French name is   Aubin  . The personal name was especially popular in Austria, Lombardy, and Savoy, where it absorbed the ancient Germanic name <i>Albuin</i> (which is composed of the elements <i>alb</i> ‘elf’ + <i>win</i> ‘friend’; compare   Alvin  ). This was the name of the Lombard leader (died 572) who made himself king of northern Italy, and also of various Christian saints, including a bishop of Brixen (Bressanone) in South Tyrol.","Galician (<b>Albín</b>): habitational name from any of the four places called Albín in Galicia (Spain), from Latin <i>(villa) Albini</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":12,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":21,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":66,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas St Aubyn was born about 1316, in Devon, England, his father, Guy St Aubyn, was 37 and his mother, Margaret Sutton, was 18. He married Alice Raleigh about 1351, in Combe Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He was buried in Combe Raleigh, Devon, England."},"et":{"about 1316–":"umbes 1316–Surnud","1314–1357":"1314–1357","1316–Male":"1316–Surnud","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1352–1383":"1352–1383","1281–1345":"1281–1345","1299–Female":"1299–Surnud","20 January 1362":"20. jaanuar 1362","1352":"1352","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1281":"1281","1316":"1316","1337":"1337